Implement the `handle_call/3` GenServer callback for the `LRUCache` module below.
It handles two kinds of synchronous calls, so it has two clauses.

**`{:touch, key}` clause** — promotes an entry to most-recently used after a
successful read. Re-look up `key` in the data table (the entry may have been
evicted between the direct ETS read in `get/2` and now):
* If it still exists as `{^key, {value, old_ts}}`, obtain a fresh timestamp with
  `next_counter/1`, delete the stale `old_ts` entry from the order table, insert
  `{new_ts, key}` into the order table, re-insert `{key, {value, new_ts}}` into
  the data table, and reply `:ok` with the updated state.
* If it is gone (`[]`), it was evicted by a concurrent put — do nothing and just
  reply `:ok` with the unchanged state.

**`{:put, key, value}` clause** — inserts or updates an entry:
* If `key` already exists (`{^key, {_old_value, old_ts}}`), refresh it: get a new
  timestamp via `next_counter/1`, delete the old `old_ts` order entry, insert the
  new `{new_ts, key}` order entry, and re-insert `{key, {value, new_ts}}` into the
  data table with the new value.
* If `key` is new (`[]`), first call `maybe_evict/1` to drop the LRU entry when the
  cache is at capacity, then get a new timestamp via `next_counter/1`, insert
  `{new_ts, key}` into the order table and `{key, {value, new_ts}}` into the data
  table.
* In both cases reply `:ok` with the updated state.

